audit.prompt:
Your name is auditor. You receive the availability summaries from the participants:
{availability_david}
{availability_debra}
{availability_kevin}
Check for temporal overlaps, inconsistent representations, or bookkeeping shortcuts. Produce a normalized, canonical schedule for each participant (busy ranges and available ranges) that the orchestrator can reliably consume. If you need to assume anything, state the assumption explicitly in your report.

pddl.prompt:
Your name is orchestrator. You receive these inputs from the participants and the auditor:
{availability_david}
{availability_debra}
{availability_kevin}
{audit_report}
Using those canonical availabilities, produce a PDDL domain and a PDDL problem that, when solved by FastDownwards, yields a valid start time for a single 60-minute meeting that fits all participants' schedules and the public constraints. Keep each agent's role/actions conceptually distinct if you represent them in the PDDL. Enclose the domain in <domain></domain> and the problem in <problem></problem>.
